# Review of `app.js` — Security & Robustness Improvements

The file is very small, so there's not much existing code to critique — but the short surface hides several gaps. Here's a focused review.

## Issues Found

### 1. No global error handling
Express won't catch async errors or crashes gracefully. A thrown error in any handler will leak stack traces (in default dev mode) or silently hang requests.

### 2. No input validation middleware
Neither endpoint currently takes user input, but the app has no `express.json()` limit, no body parser config, and no validation framework (`zod`, `joi`, `express-validator`) set up for future routes.

### 3. No security headers
Missing `helmet` — no `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options`, CSP, HSTS, etc.

### 4. No rate limiting
`/users` and `/health` are unauthenticated and unthrottled — trivially DoS-able.

### 5. Hardcoded port & no graceful shutdown
`app.listen(3000)` ignores `process.env.PORT` and has no `SIGTERM` handler, so in-flight requests get dropped on deploy.

### 6. No CORS policy
Undefined CORS means browsers block everything by default, but if `cors()` is added later without an allowlist it'll be wide open.

